//@ compile-fail
//@ error-contains: unknown escape

// A bad escape whose character is multi-byte must be reported, not crash the compiler.
//
// `escape` consumes the escaped thing with `bump`, which advances one *byte*. For a
// multi-byte character that left the position inside a UTF-8 sequence, and the string
// body resumed with `self.text[self.pos..]` — a slice at a non-boundary, which panics.
// Four bytes were enough: a quote, a backslash, and any non-ASCII character.
//
// The lexer deliberately keeps going after a bad escape so one typo does not swallow the
// rest of the file, which is exactly why it had to resume at a valid offset.
//
// The same arm also named the wrong character: `other as char` on a UTF-8 lead byte gives
// whatever that byte means in Latin-1, so `\é` was reported as `\Ã`. Found by fuzzing —
// the corpus contains multi-byte text but never a multi-byte *escape*.

use std::io;

fn main() {
    let s = "a\éb";
    io::println(s);
}
